- The remaining table scan goes from ~1,000,000 row reads to ~20 B-tree node reads plus the 50 matches (this is the index win).
- End-to-end latency typically improves on the order of **100×–1000×** — e.g. a multi-second full-scan-plus-serialize response collapsing to single-digit milliseconds. The exact factor depends on row width, total row count, and how many rows the user actually owns; the win grows as the table grows. I'm quoting a range rather than a single number because I haven't run `EXPLAIN ANALYZE` against your data — to pin it down, run the old and new queries under `EXPLAIN (ANALYZE, BUFFERS)` and compare actual time and rows read.

